                data: '<p>KROK is an examination that helps medical students to gain license based state certification for retaining the qualification of a doctor or pharmacist after enrolling in an MBBS course in Ukraine based medical colleges. </p><p>The test is conducted by the Testing Center of the Ministry of Health of Ukraine to judge whether the applicant is the right fit  for studying medical subjects associated with medicine, dentistry, pharmacy or not.  While the first test is conducted by the end of the 3 rd year of medical degree, the second one comes by the time a student completes 6th year of MBBS degree in Ukraine based medical institutes.</p> <p>The exam demands students to clear two separate tests KROK 1 and KROK 2. Most of the students often shoot a query like - <b>‘Is KROK too tough to crack than NEET?’</b></p><p>The straightforward answer is no, however there’s a ‘but’ factor working behind it. The KROK exam might not be that hard in comparison to NEET, but it’s no easy piece of cake either!</p><p>The first part of the exam, i.e. the KROK 1 deals with the candidate’s foundational concepts of science. The test helps the admission council of the medical university you’ve chosen to decide your basic applied skills when it comes to practice of medicine.</p>'
